.SH NOTES
.sp
.LP
\fB/usr/tmp\fR is currently a symbolic link to \fB/var/tmp\fR.
.sp
.LP
Previous documentation incorrectly described the numeric register \fByr\fR as being the \fBLast two digits of current year\fR. \fByr\fR is in actuality the number of years since 1900. To correctly obtain the last two digits of the current year through the year 2099, the definition given below of string register \fByy\fR can be included in a document and subsequently used to display a two-digit year. Notice that any other available one- or two-character register name can be substituted for \fByy\fR.
.sp
.in +2
.nf
\&.\e" definition of new string register yy--last two digits of year
\&.\e" use yr (# of years since 1900) if it is < 100
\&.ie \en(yr<100 .ds yy \en(yr
\&.el \e{             .\e" else, subtract 100 from yr, store in ny
\&.nr ny \en(yr-100
\&.ie \en(ny>9 \e{     .\e" use ny if it is two digits
\&.ds yy \en(ny
\&.\e" remove temporary number register ny
\&.rr ny \e}
\&.el \e{.ds yy 0
\&.\e" if ny is one digit, append it to 0
\&.as yy \en(ny
\&.rr ny \e} \e}
.fi
.in -2

